## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | ❌ Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ❌ Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | ⚠️ Obsolete, never thrown |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, leave locks held, and corrupt shared data.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken for
    /// timely cancellation — there is no forced thread abort in .NET 8.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout)
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Convenience overload preserving the original signature for
    // fire-and-forget work that cannot be made cancellation-aware.
    // ⚠️ The work will keep running past the timeout — it is NOT killed.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            ct => work(),   // token is ignored — work runs to completion
            timeout);
    }
}
```

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work is oblivious, thread gets killed
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work observes cancellation token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into I/O APIs
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **Non-cooperative work won't stop.** If the delegate ignores the token (e.g., tight CPU loop without `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`), `ExecuteWithTimeout` throws `TimeoutException` but the work keeps running on a thread pool thread. This is the biggest behavioral difference from Framework.

2. **Blocking APIs need token-aware replacements:**
   ```csharp
   // ❌ Won't respond to cancellation
   Thread.Sleep(60_000);
   stream.Read(buffer, 0, count);

   // ✅ Cancellation-aware equivalents
   await Task.Delay(60_000, ct);
   await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, ct);
   ```

3. **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** — the original code created a dedicated thread. If work is long-blocking, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to avoid starving the pool.

4. **Don't rely on the legacy overload** (`Func<T>` without token) in production — it exists only as a migration crutch. Audit all call sites and propagate `CancellationToken` through the entire call chain.
